1. for attribute in <label>
The for attribute links the <label> element to a specific form control (like <input>). Its value must match the id of the input field.
In our code, <label for="title">Title</label>
<input type="text" id="title" name="title" />
for="title" connects the label to the input with id="title".
This means when we click on the label text “Title”, the cursor automatically focuses on the associated input box. It improves accessibility (screen readers can announce the label when the input is focused).

2. name attribute in <input>
The name attribute identifies the input field when the form is submitted. It acts as the key in the key–value pair sent to the server.
Example:<input type="text" id="title" name="title" />
If the user types "My Task" and submits the form, the data sent will look like:title=My Task
Without a name, the input’s value won’t be included in the form submission.


